      <h3>How to fix a bad cup fast</h3>
      <p>If your cup tastes <strong>sour</strong>, the coffee is usually under-extracted. That just means the water did not pull enough flavor out of the grounds. Grind a little finer, steep a little longer, or use slightly hotter water. Do not change all three unless you enjoy confusion.</p>
      <p>If your cup tastes <strong>bitter</strong>, back off instead of pushing harder. Grind a touch coarser, shorten the steep, or lower the water temperature. Dark roasts especially can go from chocolatey to ashtray fast. If that keeps happening, the paper-filter clarity method usually fixes it quicker than another gadget will.</p>
      <p>If the coffee tastes <strong>muddy</strong>, it is often a filter and grind problem, not a dose problem. That is where good paper filters and a more even grinder help. Our <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-grind-size.html">AeroPress grind size guide</a> is the next read if your cups keep swinging between harsh and dull.</p>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="buying-guide">
    <BuyingGuideSection>
      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying guide: when extra gear actually helps</h2>
      <p><strong>Start with the brewer, not the gadget pile.</strong> If you are new, buy the brewer and learn the standard method first. That gives you a real baseline. Once you know whether you want more body, more strength, or better travel convenience, then the accessories make sense. Buying attachments before you know what problem you are solving is how simple brewers turn into junk drawers.</p>
      <p><strong>Add a grinder before you obsess over tiny recipe tweaks.</strong> If your grounds look like gravel mixed with dust, no method is going to save the cup. A grinder like the <a href={amazonUrl('B0833SDN8M')} rel="nofollow sponsored noopener" target="_blank">TIMEMORE Chestnut C2</a> is a much smarter upgrade than another random accessory because it makes every method here easier to repeat. Better grind consistency means fewer cups that taste bitter and sour at the same time.</p>
      <p><strong>Add a scale when you start caring about repeatability.</strong> Scoop brewing is fine for lazy Sundays, but if you want the same cup twice, weigh the coffee and the water. This matters even more with bypass methods because eyeballing the dilution is where a lot of good cups go flat. You do not need an expensive scale. You just need one that makes guessing unnecessary.</p>
      <p><strong>Add a flow-control accessory only when you know why you want it.</strong> If you love the standard method, you may not need one at all. If you want more body, fuller immersion, or easier concentrate brewing, then a <a href={amazonUrl('B079YBT2LJ')} rel="nofollow sponsored noopener" target="_blank">Prismo</a> or <a href={amazonUrl('B0BXCRVZ52')} rel="nofollow sponsored noopener" target="_blank">Flow Control Cap</a> starts to earn its spot. My general rule is simple: buy gear to solve a taste or workflow problem you already notice, not one you hope to invent later.</p>
